# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
#
# PLAN_PATCH_TEMPLATE — Per-Task Format
#
# Each task gets its own .patch file in the patches/ subfolder.
# Filename: T-{task-id}.patch
# Compatible with: patch -p1 < T-{task-id}.patch
#
# STRUCTURE:
# - One .patch file PER TASK (not one for entire plan)
# - Each file contains ALL diffs for that single task
# - Each modified/added/deleted file gets its own diff block within the task patch
# - Use unified diff format (--- a/ +++ b/)
#
# OUTPUT LOCATION:
#   documents/plans/{plan-name}/patches/T-{task-id}.patch
#
# PLACEHOLDERS:
#   [TASK_ID]          — Task identifier (T-{uuid})
#   [TASK_SUBJECT]     — Short task description
#   [FILE_PATH]        — Relative path from project root
#   [HUNK_HEADER]      — @@ -start,count +start,count @@
#
# RULES:
# 1. Include 3 lines of context around each change
# 2. New files: use /dev/null as the "a" path
# 3. Deleted files: use /dev/null as the "b" path
# 4. Group hunks logically — one per method/block change
# 5. Include ALL files affected by THIS task
# 6. Order: new files first, then modified, then deleted
# 7. Each patch must be independently reviewable
#
# === PER-TASK PATCH FORMAT ===
#
# File: patches/T-{task-id}.patch
# Task: [TASK_SUBJECT]

--- a/[FILE_PATH]
+++ b/[FILE_PATH]
[HUNK_HEADER]
 [CONTEXT_LINE_1]
 [CONTEXT_LINE_2]
 [CONTEXT_LINE_3]
-[OLD_LINE_1]
-[OLD_LINE_2]
+[NEW_LINE_1]
+[NEW_LINE_2]
+[NEW_LINE_3]
 [CONTEXT_LINE_4]
 [CONTEXT_LINE_5]
 [CONTEXT_LINE_6]

# === NEW FILE EXAMPLE ===

--- /dev/null
+++ b/[NEW_FILE_PATH]
@@ -0,0 +1,[TOTAL_LINES] @@
+[COMPLETE_FILE_CONTENT_LINE_BY_LINE]

# === DELETED FILE EXAMPLE ===

--- a/[DELETED_FILE_PATH]
+++ /dev/null
@@ -1,[TOTAL_LINES] +0,0 @@
-[COMPLETE_FILE_CONTENT_LINE_BY_LINE]

# === GENERATION RULES ===
#
# For EACH task in the plan:
#   1. Create patches/T-{task-id}.patch
#   2. Identify every file that task changes
#   3. Write the complete diff for each file
#   4. Include full method/class context (not just changed lines)
#   5. Ensure patch applies cleanly: patch -p1 --dry-run < patches/T-{id}.patch
#
# Cost-to-detail mapping:
#   S tasks: Full implementation (< 50 lines typically)
#   M tasks: Full implementation (50-150 lines typically)
#   L tasks: Full implementation (150-400 lines typically)
#   XL tasks: Full implementation (400+ lines typically)
#
# EVERY task MUST have its own .patch file.
# No task may be left without a corresponding patches/T-{id}.patch file.
#
# Also generate tasks.json alongside patches/:
#   [{"id": "T-{id}", "subject": "...", "type": "Logic", "cost": "M", "wave": 1}]
